{{ja-kanjitab|す|yomi=o}}
{{ja-kanjitab|し|yomi=o}}

From {{bor|ja|ltc|sort=し|-}} {{ltc-l|子}}, also used in the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'' (''c.'' 759 {{CE}}) as {{m|ja|借音|tr=shakuon}} ''[[kana]]'' for {{IPAfont|⟨si⟩}}. Compare modern {{cog|cmn|子|tr=zǐ}}.

The ''{{ll|ja|呉音|goon}}'' reading of ''shi'' is likely the original borrowing:
: {{IPAchar|/t͡sɨ/}} → {{IPAchar|/sɨ/}} → *{{IPAchar|/ɕɨ/}} → {{IPAchar|/ɕi/}}

The ''{{ll|ja|唐音|tōon}}'' reading ''su'' appears later, and only shows up in certain set terms borrowed from {{bor|ja|zh|sort=す|-}}, where it seems to serve as a kind of nominalizing suffix:
: {{IPAchar|/t͡sɨ/}} → {{IPAchar|/sɨ/}} → *{{IPAchar|/sʉ/}} → {{IPAchar|/su/}}

